      <section class=3D"content">

        <h1>Validation of UPC and EAN Barcode Numbers</h1>
        <p>All <a href=3D"https://go-upc.com/what-is-upc">UPCs</a> are 12-d=
igit numbers,
          but not every 12-digit number is a valid UPC.</p>
        <p>How so? Because every UPC has what's called a "<em>check digit</=
em>".
          This check digit =E2=80=94 the last digit in every UPC =E2=80=94
          helps to catch errors like typos and provide some degree of confi=
dence that
          you're actually dealing with a UPC.</p>
        <p>EAN codes are similar. Though they have 13 digits, they too have=
 a final <em>check</em>
          digit to help weed out errors.</p>

        <h2>Just because it validates...</h2>
        <p>...doesn't mean that it is an active UPC!</p>
        <p>That's right; a lot of 12-digit
          (and 13-digit) numbers will <em>=E2=80=9Cvalidate=E2=80=9D</em> a=
s a UPC (or EAN), but
          that doesn't mean the code has actually been <strong>assigned</st=
rong> to a
          product. That said, if it validates the number <strong>could</str=
ong> be assigned
          in the future, so it may wind up on a product someday.</p>
        <p>If you're wondering what product a particular number is associat=
ed with =E2=80=94 if
          any =E2=80=94 you can always <a href=3D"https://go-upc.com/">plug=
 it into our search form</a> to check against
          our database of millions of UPCs.</p>
      </section>
      <section id=3D"upc-validation-example" class=3D"content">

        <h2>How UPC Validation Works =E2=80=94 An Example</h2>

        <p>Let's break down the logic for validating a UPC. For an example,
          we'll use the code <code>82957601931<strong><u>1</u></strong></co=
de>.
          One (<code>1</code>) is the check digit in this case.</p>

        <figure style=3D"margin: 30px auto 40px; text-align: center;">
      <img src=3D"https://go-upc.com/img/upc-validation-example.png" alt=3D=
"Example UPC Barcode Validation" style=3D"width: auto; height: 125px;">
    </figure>

        <p>With the following <strong>5 steps</strong> we will confirm this=
 UPC is valid:</p>

        <ol>
          <li>
            Take all of the <em>odd</em>-position digits =E2=80=94
            the 1st, 3rd, 5th, 7th, 9th, and 11th digits =E2=80=94 and add =
them together.<br>
            <pre>8 + 9 + 7 + 0 + 9 + 1 =3D <strong>34</strong></pre>
          </li>
          <li>
            Multiply the result of step 1 (<code>34</code>) by the number <=
code>3</code>.<br>
            <pre>34 * 3 =3D <strong>102</strong></pre>
          </li>
          <li>
            Now, take all of the <em>even</em>-position digits (positions 2=
, 4, 6, 8 and 10),
            and add them together.<br>
            <pre>2 + 5 + 6 + 1 + 3 =3D <strong>17</strong></pre>
          </li>
          <li>
            Take the sum of the results from steps 2 and 3.<br>
            <pre>102 + 17 =3D <strong>119</strong></pre>
          </li>
          <li>
            The check digit is calculated by figuring out what number needs=
 to be added to the
            result of step 4 in order to make it a multiple of 10.<br>
            <pre>119 + <span style=3D"color: green">1</span> =3D <strong>12=
0</strong></pre>
          </li>
        </ol>

        <p>Therefore, the check digit for this UPC barcode is <code>1</code=
>.</p>
      </section>
      <section id=3D"ean-validation-example" class=3D"content">

        <h2>Example EAN Validation</h2>

        <p>Validating an EAN is very similar; we're just dealing with one a=
dditional digit.
          For this example, we'll use the code <code>590004900361<strong><u=
>9</u></strong></code>.
        </p>

        <figure style=3D"margin: 30px auto 40px; text-align: center;">
      <img src=3D"https://go-upc.com/img/ean-validation-example.png" alt=3D=
"Example EAN Barcode Validation" style=3D"width: auto; height: 125px;">
    </figure>

        <p>Here are the 5 steps to validate this EAN code:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            Take all of the <em>odd</em>-position digits (exluding position=
 13, since this last
            number is the check digit), and add them together.<br>
            <pre>5 + 0 + 0 + 9 + 0 + 6 =3D <strong>20</strong></pre>
          </li>
          <li>
            Now, take all of the <em>even</em>-position digits (positions 2=
, 4, 6, 8, 10, and 12),
            and add them together.<br>
            <pre>9 + 0 + 4 + 0 + 3 + 1 =3D <strong>17</strong></pre>
          </li>
          <li>
            Multiply the result of step 2 (<code>17</code>) by the number <=
code>3</code>.<br>
            <pre>17 * 3 =3D <strong>51</strong></pre>
          </li>
          <li>
            Take the sum of the results from steps 1 and 3.<br>
            <pre>20 + 51 =3D <strong>71</strong></pre>
          </li>
          <li>
            The check digit is calculated by figuring out what number needs=
 to be added to the
            result of step 4 in order to make it a multiple of 10.<br>
            <pre>71 + <span style=3D"color: green">9</span> =3D <strong>80<=
/strong></pre>
          </li>
        </ol>
        <p>Therefore, the check digit for this EAN barcode is <code>9</code=
>, and we confirm
          that <code>5900049003619</code> is a valid EAN.</p>
      </section>
